FILARIASIS - INDONESIA (JAMBI)
********************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Tue 23 Jan 2007
From: Thomas Schmidt <mediscon@web.de>
Source: Jakarta Post online [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailnational.asp?fileid=20070123.G11&irec=10>

The preventable but disfiguring disease of
elephantiasis is on the rise in Jambi, with 277
people diagnosed with the illness during the past
5 years, a health official says.
Anwar Djauhari of Jambi Health Office's
communicable disease eradication section said the
cases were recorded in three of the province's 10
regions. The 3 regencies -- Muarojambi and West
and East Tanjungjabung -- are located in swampy
areas or peat lands, he said. The office had
treated the illness at clinics in the 3
regencies, Azwar said. However, more clinics were
needed to prevent the disease from spreading, he said.
Elephantiasis, which is caused by the invasion of
lymphatic glands by tiny worms, leads to the
gross swelling of limbs or the scrotum. Azwar
said the office had warned villagers in the 3
regencies to maintain sanitation standards around
residential areas. They should also guard against
being bitten by mosquitoes, which help spread the disease, he said.
--
